            "answer_text": "If f(y) is the probability density function of y, you have to integrate it from c to infinity, then integrate it multiplied by y from c to infinity and divide the latter by the former. For example, with a uniform distribution from a < c < b, the integral from c to b (you don\u2019t need to go up to infinity because the domain of the distribution stops at b) is (b - c) / (b - a). If you multiply by y, the integral from c to b is (b^2 - c^2)/[2*(b - a). If you divide the latter by the former, you get (b^2 - c^2)/[2*(b - c)] = (b + c)/2. For a standard Normal distribution, the integral from c to infinity is 1 - N(c). If you multiply by y and integrate, you get exp(-c^2/2)/sqrt(2*pi). If you divide the former by the latter, you get exp(-c^2/2)/[sqrt(2*pi)*(1 - N(c))]. You\u2019ll get different formulae for different distributions, but this is the method. ",
